<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,153,531]" box="[151,1436,186,208]" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,186,208]" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">
1. Prosternal basantra fully sclerotized as discrete sclerites (
<figureCitation box="[775,834,186,208]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1568,1590]" captionTargetBox="[151,1429,559,1539]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1435,559,1539]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Hoplothrips species. H. hongruiae sp. n. 1–5: (1) Head &amp; pronotum; (2) Antenna; (3) Male sternite VIII; (4) Pelta &amp; tergites II–III; (5) Prosternum &amp; mesopresternum. (6) H. fungosus prosternites. Antennal segments III–IV 7–8: (7) H. corticis; (8) H. orientalis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3734659" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3734659/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
); male sternite VIII without a pore plate.......... 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moulton" authorityYear="1928" box="[1351,1436,186,207]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Hoplothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="597" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fungosus">
<emphasis box="[1351,1436,186,207]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">fungosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,153,531]" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">
<keyLead pageId="1" pageNumber="597">
-. Prosternal basantra not present as discrete sclerites but several chitinous islets are sometimes closely associated (
<figureCitation box="[1312,1371,215,237]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1568,1590]" captionTargetBox="[151,1429,559,1539]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1435,559,1539]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Hoplothrips species. H. hongruiae sp. n. 1–5: (1) Head &amp; pronotum; (2) Antenna; (3) Male sternite VIII; (4) Pelta &amp; tergites II–III; (5) Prosternum &amp; mesopresternum. (6) H. fungosus prosternites. Antennal segments III–IV 7–8: (7) H. corticis; (8) H. orientalis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3734659" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3734659/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
); male with broad pore plate on sternite VIII (
<figureCitation box="[597,654,245,267]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1568,1590]" captionTargetBox="[151,1429,559,1539]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1435,559,1539]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Hoplothrips species. H. hongruiae sp. n. 1–5: (1) Head &amp; pronotum; (2) Antenna; (3) Male sternite VIII; (4) Pelta &amp; tergites II–III; (5) Prosternum &amp; mesopresternum. (6) H. fungosus prosternites. Antennal segments III–IV 7–8: (7) H. corticis; (8) H. orientalis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3734659" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3734659/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
)............................................................... 2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="1" pageNumber="597">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,153,531]" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">
<keyLead pageId="1" pageNumber="597">
2. Female with no fore tarsal tooth; maxillary stylets 0.2–0.3 of head width apart (
<figureCitation box="[1007,1065,274,296]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1568,1590]" captionTargetBox="[151,1429,559,1539]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1435,559,1539]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Hoplothrips species. H. hongruiae sp. n. 1–5: (1) Head &amp; pronotum; (2) Antenna; (3) Male sternite VIII; (4) Pelta &amp; tergites II–III; (5) Prosternum &amp; mesopresternum. (6) H. fungosus prosternites. Antennal segments III–IV 7–8: (7) H. corticis; (8) H. orientalis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3734659" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3734659/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), maxillary bridge distinct; prosternal basantra weakly indicated by series of coalescing chitinous islets; mesopresternum complete (
<figureCitation box="[1146,1207,303,325]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1568,1590]" captionTargetBox="[151,1429,559,1539]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1435,559,1539]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Hoplothrips species. H. hongruiae sp. n. 1–5: (1) Head &amp; pronotum; (2) Antenna; (3) Male sternite VIII; (4) Pelta &amp; tergites II–III; (5) Prosternum &amp; mesopresternum. (6) H. fungosus prosternites. Antennal segments III–IV 7–8: (7) H. corticis; (8) H. orientalis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3734659" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3734659/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
); body length less than 2000 microns............................................................................ 
<taxonomicName authority="Mound &amp; Wang, 2020" authorityName="Mound &amp; Wang" authorityYear="2020" box="[1284,1383,333,354]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Hoplothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="597" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hongruiae" status="sp.n.">
<emphasis box="[1284,1383,333,354]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">hongruiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1388,1437,333,354]" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1388,1437,333,354]" pageId="1" pageNumber="597" rank="species">sp.n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,153,531]" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">
<keyLead pageId="1" pageNumber="597">-. Female with fore tarsal tooth well-developed; maxillary stylets close together medially in head without a maxillary bridge; prosternal basantra clearly absent; mesopresternum reduced to pair of lateral triangles; body length at least 3000 microns... 3</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="1" pageNumber="597">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,153,531]" box="[151,1437,421,443]" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">
<keyLead box="[151,1437,421,443]" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">
3. Antennal segment III sense cones short and straight (
<figureCitation box="[734,792,421,443]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1568,1590]" captionTargetBox="[151,1429,559,1539]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1435,559,1539]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Hoplothrips species. H. hongruiae sp. n. 1–5: (1) Head &amp; pronotum; (2) Antenna; (3) Male sternite VIII; (4) Pelta &amp; tergites II–III; (5) Prosternum &amp; mesopresternum. (6) H. fungosus prosternites. Antennal segments III–IV 7–8: (7) H. corticis; (8) H. orientalis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3734659" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3734659/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
).......................................... 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="De Geer" baseAuthorityYear="1773" box="[1300,1372,421,442]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Hoplothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="597" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="corticis">
